The baseline harness does not evaluate the advertised fused-rerank comparator because it reranks the engine's own capped pool instead of the fused BM25+dense pool. This makes the primary baseline numbers unreliable; the power-shape issue further distorts reported simulations.

Full review comments:

- [P1] Rerank the fused pool instead of the engine default pool — /tmp/fdb-0.8.2-slice-5-20260618T154504Z/src/python/eval/m1_baseline.py:430-431
  For the `fused_rerank` arm, this calls the reranker with only the raw query/passages and ignores the `fused` ranking computed just above. `Engine.search()` constructs its own production pool, which is capped by the engine search limit before CE reranking, so on the ~20-passage MuSiQue questions with the default `top_k=10` the answerer sees CE-reranked engine-top-10 hits rather than `RRF(bm25, dense)` reranked over the identical per-question pool. This changes the fixed comparator whenever a relevant passage is outside the engine pool but inside the in-harness fused top-k.

- [P2] Center the inverted-U effect before simulating power — /tmp/fdb-0.8.2-slice-5-20260618T154504Z/src/python/eval/m1_power_sim.py:66-68
  The inverted-U shape is documented as having pooled mean approximately equal to `lift`, but this formula adds a non-negative bump on top of `lift`. In the actual pooled ≥3-hop sample, any 3-hop questions raise the mean effect above the pre-registered +0.03 lift (for the default 65/35 3/4-hop mix it is about 0.0456), so the reported P(GO) for this shape is inflated and not comparable to the flat/monotonic shapes.
